message.content:
We need to “get to” the tax‐payable number by “adding” up the tax amounts recorded on sales (since taxes collected create a liability that will show as “tax payable” on a cash flow statement). In our data only the sale transactions include a nonempty tax_amount field. (Other types – deposits, purchases, expenses, depreciation, interest – do not have an entry under “tax_amount”.) Thus we pick out each “Sale…” row and add its tax_amount.

Let’s list them along with their tax_amount value:

1. Sale20240103001: 56,320.16  
2. Sale20240106004: 34,227.94  
3. Sale20240107005: 67,705.31  
4. Sale20240108008: 54,095.51  
5. Sale20240109009: 103,524.98  
6. Sale20240111011: 110,752.24  
7. Sale20240117017: 35,150.46  
8. Sale20240122024: 32,625.45  
9. Sale20240124028: 36,846.43  
10. Sale20240125030: 65,921.12  
11. Sale20240129034: 97,616.11  
12. Sale20240131038: 101,127.37  
13. Sale20240205042: 107,208.81  

Now we add them step‐by‐step:

• 56,320.16 + 34,227.94 = 90,548.10  
• 90,548.10 + 67,705.31 = 158,253.41  
• 158,253.41 + 54,095.51 = 212,348.92  
• 212,348.92 + 103,524.98 = 315,873.90  
• 315,873.90 + 110,752.24 = 426,626.14  
• 426,626.14 + 35,150.46 = 461,776.60  
• 461,776.60 + 32,625.45 = 494,402.05  
• 494,402.05 + 36,846.43 = 531,248.48  
• 531,248.48 + 65,921.12 = 597,169.60  
• 597,169.60 + 97,616.11 = 694,785.71  
• 694,785.71 + 101,127.37 = 795,913.08  
• 795,913.08 + 107,208.81 = 903,121.89  

Thus the final “Increase (Decrease) in Tax Payable” is 903121.89.
